grep — searching for text.

grep is your line filter. The name stands for "global regular expression print," and what it does is simple: it reads input one line at a time, prints the lines that match a pattern, and throws away the rest. After ls, it's probably the most-typed command in all of Linux.

It comes in three shapes. You can search a file directly, by giving grep a pattern and a filename. You can search several files at once. Or, most powerfully, you can pipe another command's output into grep to filter it, like piping ps into grep to find a process. The pattern can be a plain string or a full regular expression, which is the next section. For now, get in the habit of putting the pattern in quotes, so the shell keeps its hands off it.

Let's go through the flags you'll use constantly. Dash-i makes the match case-insensitive. Dash-v inverts it, printing the lines that don't match, which is great for filtering noise out. Dash-n prefixes each result with its line number. Dash-c prints just the count of matching lines instead of the lines themselves. Dash-r recurses down into directories. Dash-l prints only the filenames that contain a match, rather than the matches. Dash-w matches whole words only.

And three that go together: dash-capital-A followed by a number prints that many lines after each match, dash-capital-B prints lines before, and dash-capital-C prints lines of context on both sides. Those are invaluable when you're reading logs. Two more: dash-capital-F treats the pattern as a fixed string rather than a regex, which is faster and saves you escaping. And dash-capital-E turns on extended regular expressions, which you'll almost always want, and which is exactly what the next section is about.

One tip: if you find yourself searching through code a lot, install ripgrep, the rg command. It's a modern grep that's dramatically faster, automatically respects your gitignore file, and has saner regex defaults out of the box.
